    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the previous detour. Let's get straight to the heart of the matter. The interest on a student loan is typically calculated using the following formula:\n\nInterest = Principal Balance × Interest Rate / Number of Payments per Year\n\nSo, every month, the interest charged is based on the remaining principal balance of your loan. As you make payments, the principal balance decreases, which in turn reduces the amount of interest charged each month. However, if your payments are mostly covering the interest and only a small portion is going towards the principal, the balance won't decrease significantly, and you'll continue to see a substantial interest charge. This is why it can feel like your money is disappearing into a void. To see the impact more clearly, you can create a simple amortization schedule that breaks down each payment into interest and principal components. This will show you exactly how much of your payment is going towards reducing the principal and how much is going towards the interest.",
