      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok that makes sense. so if i want to pay this off faster, is it better to just pay more than the minimum every month? and does that extra money go straight to the principal or does it still get eaten up by interest first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely, paying more than the minimum each month is a wise strategy to pay off your student loan faster. When you make an extra payment, it goes directly to the principal balance, reducing the amount of interest you'll pay in the future. This is because the interest is calculated on the remaining balance, so the lower the balance, the less interest you'll accrue.\n\nTo illustrate, imagine you're in a battle with a goblin who charges you for every step you take. If you defeat the goblin quickly, you pay less in total. Similarly, by paying more towards the principal, you reduce the \"steps\" the goblin can take against you, meaning less interest over time.\n\nIt's like throwing a few extra gold coins into the goblin's sack right away, rather than letting it grow and grow. The more you reduce the principal early on, the less interest you'll have to pay in the long run, and the faster you'll be able to claim victory over your student loan debt.",
